</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,455,2029]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Stramineous, with or without small black spots on dorsum of thorax and forewing (
<figureCitation box="[1139,1210,455,480]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1678,1700]" captionTargetBox="[158,1427,193,1655]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[158,1428,193,1657]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Dorsal and lateral habitus. A, B, Decliviassus bipunctatus sp. nov.; C, D, Decliviassus maculatus sp. nov.; E, F, Decliviassus nudus sp. nov.; G, H, Kanchanaburiassus maculatus sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/253712/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Fig. 
<number box="[1196,1210,456,480]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
A–F). Body robust, cylindrical, not or only weakly depressed (
<figureCitation box="[636,704,492,517]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1678,1700]" captionTargetBox="[158,1427,193,1655]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[158,1428,193,1657]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Dorsal and lateral habitus. A, B, Decliviassus bipunctatus sp. nov.; C, D, Decliviassus maculatus sp. nov.; E, F, Decliviassus nudus sp. nov.; G, H, Kanchanaburiassus maculatus sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/253712/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Fig. 
<number box="[690,704,492,516]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
A–F). Head in dorsal view narrower than pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[1307,1375,492,517]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1678,1700]" captionTargetBox="[158,1427,193,1655]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[158,1428,193,1657]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Dorsal and lateral habitus. A, B, Decliviassus bipunctatus sp. nov.; C, D, Decliviassus maculatus sp. nov.; E, F, Decliviassus nudus sp. nov.; G, H, Kanchanaburiassus maculatus sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/253712/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Fig. 
<number box="[1361,1375,492,516]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
A, C, E); crown not developed, vertex vertical or nearly so, very short or not visible in dorsal view (
<figureCitation box="[1194,1260,527,552]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1678,1700]" captionTargetBox="[158,1427,193,1655]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[158,1428,193,1657]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Dorsal and lateral habitus. A, B, Decliviassus bipunctatus sp. nov.; C, D, Decliviassus maculatus sp. nov.; E, F, Decliviassus nudus sp. nov.; G, H, Kanchanaburiassus maculatus sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/253712/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Fig. 
<number box="[1246,1260,528,552]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
A, C, E); vertex and frontoclypeus transversely rugose; face distinctly broader than tall; gena obtusely emarginate below eye; rostrum slender, extended slightly beyond front trochanter; anteclypeus convex, tapered from base to apex, apex truncate, even with lower margin of gena; lorum narrow, well separated from lateral and ventral margins of gena, with basal fourth of mesal margin bordering frontoclypeus; frontoclypeus convex; antennal ledge well developed, broad, transverse; lateral frontal suture nearly obsolete, extended only short distance above antennal ledge; ocellus large, directly above antennal pit and distant from eye (
<figureCitation box="[782,850,743,768]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1678,1700]" captionTargetBox="[158,1427,193,1655]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[158,1428,193,1657]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Dorsal and lateral habitus. A, B, Decliviassus bipunctatus sp. nov.; C, D, Decliviassus maculatus sp. nov.; E, F, Decliviassus nudus sp. nov.; G, H, Kanchanaburiassus maculatus sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/253712/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Fig. 
<number box="[835,850,744,768]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
B, D, F). Pronotum strongly convex, nearly vertical anteriorly, transversely rugose; lateral margins long, strongly carinate, evenly divergent posterad (
<figureCitation box="[1265,1333,780,805]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1678,1700]" captionTargetBox="[158,1427,193,1655]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[158,1428,193,1657]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Dorsal and lateral habitus. A, B, Decliviassus bipunctatus sp. nov.; C, D, Decliviassus maculatus sp. nov.; E, F, Decliviassus nudus sp. nov.; G, H, Kanchanaburiassus maculatus sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/253712/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Fig. 
<number box="[1319,1333,780,804]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
A, C, E). Exposed part of mesonotum and scutellum together distinctly shorter than pronotum, transversely rugose; scutellar suture arched anterad, scutellum weakly convex with apex acute (
<figureCitation box="[906,975,852,877]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1678,1700]" captionTargetBox="[158,1427,193,1655]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[158,1428,193,1657]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Dorsal and lateral habitus. A, B, Decliviassus bipunctatus sp. nov.; C, D, Decliviassus maculatus sp. nov.; E, F, Decliviassus nudus sp. nov.; G, H, Kanchanaburiassus maculatus sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/253712/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Fig. 
<number box="[961,975,852,876]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
A, C, E). Forewing venation moderately well delimited; membrane opaquely sclerotized in basal 
<number box="[803,818,888,912]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="2.0">2</number>
/ 
<number box="[828,841,888,912]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="3.0">3</number>
, with or without numerous small black spots; setae very short, fine, and inconspicuous; appendix broad, extended to wing apex, slightly narrower than inner apical cell; vein R with 
<number box="[373,415,959,984]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="6.0" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="5.0">5–7</number>
branches; three closed anteapical cells present; apical cells 
<number box="[1149,1192,960,984]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="2.5" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="1.0">1–4</number>
long, parallel-sided, progressively longer toward trailing edge of wing, bases not aligned; posterior branch of CuA connected to margin at apex of clavus; clavus truncate apically; texture of inner apical cell same as that of appendix and adjacent apical cell (
<figureCitation box="[208,275,1068,1093]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1678,1700]" captionTargetBox="[158,1427,193,1655]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[158,1428,193,1657]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Dorsal and lateral habitus. A, B, Decliviassus bipunctatus sp. nov.; C, D, Decliviassus maculatus sp. nov.; E, F, Decliviassus nudus sp. nov.; G, H, Kanchanaburiassus maculatus sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/253712/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Fig. 
<number box="[261,275,1068,1092]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
A–F). Front femur with pair of dorsoapical macrosetae and AM 
<number box="[1003,1012,1068,1092]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="1.0">1</number>
well developed but PD, AD and AM without well differentiated preapical setae; intercalary group consisting of irregular double row of moderately stout setae continuous with setae of similar size in basal AV group; PV with several well differentiated macrosetae; tibia with dorsal surface flat and bicarinate, AD and PD each with 
<number box="[848,889,1176,1200]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="7.5" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="7.0">7–8</number>
macrosetae. Mesothoracic femur PD with 
<number box="[1374,1388,1176,1200]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="2.0">2</number>
and AD with 
<number box="[254,268,1212,1237]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="6.0">6</number>
macrosetae; ventral setae poorly differentiated. 
<collectingCountry box="[804,860,1212,1237]" name="India" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Hind</collectingCountry>
femur macrosetae 
<number box="[1071,1086,1212,1236]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="2.0">2</number>
+ 
<number box="[1103,1118,1212,1236]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="2.0">2</number>
+ 
<number box="[1135,1145,1212,1236]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="1.0">1</number>
with antepenultimate seta as large as others; tibial rows PD, AD, and AV with 20, 12, and 
<number box="[885,913,1247,1272]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="15.0">15</number>
macrosetae, respectively; tarsomere I without dorsoapical setae, plantar surface bare, pecten with 
<number box="[728,742,1284,1309]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="6.0">6</number>
platellae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,455,2029]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Male abdominal apodemes poorly developed. Sternite VIII ca. twice as long as sternite VII, longer than broad, lateral margins tapered posterad, apex convexly produced. Genital capsule with posteroventral part almost completely concealed by sternite VIII in repose, with only anal tube and part of posterior pygofer margin visible. Pygofer with tergite long, well sclerotized, narrowly emarginate distally in dorsal view; lobes elongated, acutely angulate, with posterodorsal group of several macrosetae; posterior setal group undifferentiated, posterior margin long and straight, with short basolateral process bearing two or more lobes (
<figureCitation box="[995,1079,1500,1525]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1574,1596]" captionTargetBox="[190,1399,205,1542]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[177,1409,193,1552]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 10. The holotype of Decliviassus bipunctatus sp. nov. A. Genital capsule, lateral view; B. Aedeagus, lateral view; C. Style, lateral view; D. Subgenital plates, ventral view; E. Ventral process of pygofer side, caudolateral view; F. Apex of aedeagus, ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/253719/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Figs 
<number box="[1051,1079,1500,1524]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="10.0">10</number>
</figureCitation>
E, 
<number box="[1110,1137,1500,1524]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="11.0">11</number>
C, 
<number box="[1169,1197,1500,1524]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="12.0">12</number>
E, 
<number box="[1227,1256,1500,1524]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="13.0">13</number>
B); anterodorsal margin in lateral view emarginate along intersegmental membrane; intersegmental membrane between anal tube and aedeagal atrium without accessory lobes, sclerites, or setae; basolateral setal group absent (
<figureCitation box="[1256,1344,1572,1597]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1574,1596]" captionTargetBox="[190,1399,205,1542]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[177,1409,193,1552]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 10. The holotype of Decliviassus bipunctatus sp. nov. A. Genital capsule, lateral view; B. Aedeagus, lateral view; C. Style, lateral view; D. Subgenital plates, ventral view; E. Ventral process of pygofer side, caudolateral view; F. Apex of aedeagus, ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/253719/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
